<br>
On the other hand, Phinny's a linked spawn. The main reason you clear the swirlspines out before you pull, is that when you pull you're going to get it all.<br>
<br>
I've actually verified this in one phinny camp, when the raid leader asked me to stand up ... and I did. Basically, we had a Guardian on the ledge sitting on the corpses from the first attempt. They were doing res and CR, and the raid leader asked me to stand up to re-aggro the Guardian if he started to leave (I'd managed to feign during the wipeout, and by the time the CR was going had mended up to healthy).<br>
<br>
Well, they were about halfway done CR, the Guardian started to leave. I sent out a warning OOC, stood up. Guardian came for me. Phinny came for me. Four swirlspines came for me. I squeaked. Feigned. Got hit by the slow-casting Wrath one of the swirlies put on me, feign broken, exceedingly dead monk.<br>
<br>
But basically, you win the whole room if you aggro Phinny and anything's up, was my experience. So your train may not have been a train per se, but just you pulling Phin while they were engaging the swirlspines (and then Phin sharing hate with the swirlspines, and you getting The Big Win summons again and again). You're lucky the adds didn't CH the punk repeatedly, it's happened to me before.<br>
<br>
And I'm REAL glad you got your staff, but I fear for you in the review. VI's twisted and loves to stick to the letter of the law. By that, you leapfrogged them, I think, from your account. They moved past your group (which wasn't engaged, but was in a position to engage). This is where you might win. If you don't, though, and their first to engage the first seahorse... you leapfrogged by the same set of rules. Since they were busy with guards you had to clear, and you went for the lootholder (Phinny), they might decide YOU broke the policy, even though the other guild screwed you in the first place.<br>
<br>
Good luck though. I hate seeing the asses win, and I hope they don't in your case.<br>
<br>
Sutekh/Kephra<br>
